deck_excerpt: It's almost entirely playsets of cards that are banned/restricted on Master Duel.
deck_description: It's almost entirely playsets of cards that are banned/restricted on Master Duel.

As of now, there's 3 DMC lists in the works right now. They are Dogmatika Charmer Magistus, Diabellestar Charmer Magistus, and Diabellestar Centurion Magistus.

Here's a different way to play Centurion if interested in not just Calamity Turbo (or if it gets banned).

Any Centurion starter card allows you to make Zoroa on your opp turn, to lock them out after you know what they are playing. If you open Emblema, Diabellestar, Zoroa, you can end on I:P, Possessed Partnerships, Zoroa Lock, and the board wipe Sinful Spoil.

In my testing, This deck loses to Nibiru if you try to extend super hard, so if anyone can map out lines that play around Nibiru it would be appreciated. Shame that Primera has a once per turn SS restriction as well.

Hope you enjoy the list!

test

Greetings! In this deck, we will burn our opponent to death with Scarlight. For context, we will try to fill the board as many Effect Monsters as possible and detonate them all with Scarlight. "Shien's Spy" can pass some to opposing side to not feel overloaded while you will take as many turns as you can with Arcana.

 

 

Gameplan

1) Place "ME-PSY-YA" on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon "Chaos Emperor Dragon" to where Saryuja points to. From here on, pick up spells needed with "Primal Seed". As long as you target "Primal Seed" each other, it won't be a huge deal.

2) Place "Light Barrier" and Special Summon "Arcana", either via "Saryuja" or "Monster Reborn". Pick the outcome to heads to take as many turns as you like.

3) Then, place "Cynet Universe" to make sure the attack values of Chaos and Saryuja are higher than Scarlight to not detonate both by accident.

4) Revive Effect Monsters with "Monster Reborn" and pass to your opponent with "Shien's Spy". When everything is full, trigger Scarlight to unload a huge damage.

5) End your turn and deliver two of your monsters to GY and take an extra turn. No matter what, you shouldn't send Arcana+Chaos+Saryuja+Scarlight to GY.

6) Repeat what was explained into #4 and #5 until your opponent is dead. Also, shuffle back a Normal Monster into your deck with "Cynet Universe" to not deck out.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Monster Reborn" is given for free, if you have played the tutorial to save 30 UR!

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Primal Seed" + "Ravenous" + "Pot of Acquisitiveness" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 60 SR and 60 UR!

- "Arcana Force" + "Light Barrier" can be found within "Hand of Fate" Secret Pack to save 30 SR and 30 UR!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Dugares" can be found within "Number Recall" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Scarlight" can be found within "Savage Crimson Dragon" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 60 SR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 600 SR and 150 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. Let me know if you have any questions and have fun in Master Duel!

deck_excerpt: FTK, no Bishbaalkin, no other Main Deck cards needed, doesn't lose to ash.
deck_description:
To start the Main Combo, get either two Telefons or Telefons+Platinum Gadget on field.

Two Telefons: https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=721052-52614349

Telefons + Platinum Gadget: https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=721052-52617894

 

If your opponent is occupying a zone (requires three Telefons):

(Left occupied): https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=721052-52707429

(Right occupied): https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=721052-52707915

 

Tips:

Your goal every game is to get 2+ Telefons into rotation and OTK your opponent.

Therion "King" Regulus acts as both negation and an extender to get out Platinum Gadget.

Small world bridges usually end with Gizmek Naganaki (Light). Use its first effect to get Telefon, second effect to get whatever your small world bridge was (typically another Telefon or Gizmek Orochi (Dark)).

Cyberse Clock Dragon is not a hard once per turn. The second summon needs to be chain blocked by Clock Lizard's effect to avoid ash blossom. Pay attention to remaining cards in deck when fusion summoning using material from grave; you have to mill the exact amount.

 

Extra Deck is extremely tight now that Bishbaalkin is banned. There may be other options if you allow yourself some main deck bricks. Machu Mech is a fun and interactive card for both players.

Creator: 维尼写

Tournament: Superbrand Top Deck   - August 26th 2023

Placement: Champion

This deck is a pile of some very powerful engines put together so that you can end up summoning enough threats to win.

It uses a "Superheavy Samurai" engine to get plays going. If you draw into a bike you can use its effect to search for wakaushi and start some synchro plays. If this doesn't work the deck also runs an "Adventure Token" engine to be able to get out an omni-negate. There is also a "Tearlaments" package along with the Ishizu cards to be able to summon out monsters such as "Predaplant Dracostapelia" and "Tearlaments Kaleido-Heart". Finally there is a small "Kashtira" package to be able to get out some powerful cards to disrupt opponents plays.

deck_excerpt: Cyber Summon Blaster Burn ft. Arcana+Primal Seed
deck_description:
Hello and welcome to another guide, where I'll be explaining how to burn your opponent down with "Cyber Summon Blaster" thanks to taking extra turns with Arcana and reviving back and forth a Machine monster. Let me explain.

 

Gameplan

1) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon "Chaos Emperor Dragon". From here on, use "Primal Seed" cards to cycle combo pieces. As long as you target "Primal Seed" cards with each other, it won't be a problem.

2) Place "Light Barrier" and Special Summon Arcana, either via Saryuja or with "Monster Reborn", if discarded by Dugares/Ravenous. Choose the outcome of heads to skip your opponent's turn at the cost of two of your monsters being delivered to GY. Don't send Arcana and Chaos by accident and make sure you have two monsters available, which can be arranged with "Monster Reborn".

3) Set all of "Cyber Summon Blaster" and one of "Primal Seed" cards. End your turn but not before changing "Activation Confirmation" to "Switch+Hold" and setting to "ON" in-game to not miss any action, which can be edited in "Duel" section of settings page.

4) It's your turn now. Activate all of "Cyber Summon Blaster" trap cards.

5) Now, here is infinite burn. Revive a Machine monster (e.g: Martial) with "Monster Reborn" and destroy it with "Offerings to the Doomed". Rinse and repeat for constant 300 x 3 = 900 damage in total until your opponent is dead.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Monster Reborn" is given for free, if you have completed tutorial to save 30 UR!

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contact Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Arcana" + "Light Barrier" can be found within "Hand of Fate" Secret Pack to save 30 SR and 30 UR!

- "Number 60: Dugares the Timeless" can be found within "Number Recall" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Pot of Acquisitiveness" + "Primal Seed" + "Ravenous" + "Cyber Summon Blaster" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 150 SR and 60 UR!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 90 SR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 690 SR and 150 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. Let me know if you have any questions and have fun in Master Duel!

deck_excerpt: Fascinating analysis of your future, lucky or unlucky?
deck_description:
On the world geopolitical stage, the Third War was in full force. The United States, known for its global influence, made a serious mistake in underestimating the power of the enemy. After intense conflict, China has emerged as a formidable force, imbued with impressive military might. However, amid this turmoil, an unexpected partnership began to play a significant role in the war: Brazil.

Quietly, Brazil, driven by a sense of justice and solidarity, decided to help China in its battle against the European powers. Help arrived in a variety of ways, from the full of economic resources to the leak of American information to the Chinese on Brazilian soil.

Meanwhile, in the United States, authorities frantically debated where this crucial aid to the enemy came from. Military analysts, with their sharp minds, combed through countless intelligence reports, trying to figure out where these essential resources for China came from. However, the secret of Brazil and China was well guarded, unable to be unraveled.

Amidst this geopolitical strife, a new voice has begun to emerge: that of America's youth. Tired of seeing their country's youth sent to the battlefield, they refused to join the war. A large demonstration was raised among the American population who did not want to have their children killed in the war, a wave of protests across the country.

This insurrection, however, was not enough to change the course of the war. Hostilities continued, and as the months passed, the United States found itself increasingly weak. China, in collaboration with Russia, Brazil and South Africa, formed a powerful and efficient alliance, leaving the Americans with no way out.

In the end, the defeat of the United States was decisive. The military power of the United Nations against the country was overwhelming and, gradually, its lines of defense were being broken. China has emerged as a big winner, sealing its position as a world superpower alongside its powerful allies Brazil, Russia and South Africa.

deck_excerpt: What would Kyoji Yagumo have used at the start of his dueling career?
deck_description:
As an exercise, I'm attempting to derive deck designs for Zexal characters as they would be near the start of the XYZ era (assuming that card release order was mostly like our own). Manga villain Kyoji Yagumo is known for his signature Spider and Underworld cards, but as he's only seen Dueling late in the series, we have no evidence he had all of those cards back when he was participating in tournaments long before Yuma's story started.

As part of the exercise, this deck uses no cards from later than Generation Force. But if anyone has any thoughts about other cards or strategies better suited to the era, or sees something else I missed, feel free to comment. Remember that Synchros are unavailable, as Zexal tries to pretend those don't exist.

deck_excerpt: What would Kite's deck have looked like at the start of his Number-hunting career?
deck_description:
As an exercise, I'm looking at Zexal characters and deriving what their decks might have looked like at the dawn of the XYZ era (Assuming that card release order still mostly resembled our own). With Kite, I actually have a lot to work with, as he was seen using many cards from Photon Shockwave in his introductory duel, along with a few older cards. (Though it's strange that he was using Goddess with the Third Eye as a filler. Even when he got a Fusion monster later that season, fusion substitutes don't work for it.)

As part of the exercise, I'm assuming Kite was one of the first people to get cards from the Photon Shockwave set (even aside from the Photon monsters which would not have been distributed to the public in that world). It's a privilege of working for the people designing and printing the cards in his world. But anything past that wasn't even on the drawing board when he was initially fielded. That said, if there's anything that can be done to refine the deck within these restrictions, feel free to make suggestions.

deck_excerpt: What did Quattro use at the dawn of XYZ - wait, we already know that!
deck_description:
Quattro, born Thomas Arclight, became synonymous with the Gimmick Puppet archetype once he entered the spotlight of Zexal's storyline. Before they were printed, one might have expected him to have tried out Wind-ups... but actually (as Shark was disqualified for seeing) months before the Numbers were unleashed, this young showman was a favorite to win with a Gravekeeper deck.

 

This is based on an actual real-life tournament-winning deck from around 2010-2011, with a few swap-outs for cards that we (and Shark) canonically saw spilled on the floor. It's also lacking an extra deck, as rank 4s seemingly didn't exist yet, and the monster lineup can't manage anything else. (Tremendous Fire is a stand-in for a certain blazing card that doesn't actually exist.) Even so, one can still see how a well-worn deck like this would have taken victory against the newer, uncertain decks in the very first days of XYZ.

Though, perhaps there's something I'm overlooking about how decks were constructed in those days...

deck_excerpt: I asked ChatGPT to make a Synchron Deck.
deck_description:
Prompt: Create a Yu-Gi-Oh Deck that utilizes the "Synchron" archetype to summon multiple Synchro monsters on the first turn.

 

Response: "Creating a Yu-Gi-Oh! deck that focuses on the "Synchron" archetype to summon multiple Synchro monsters on the first turn is an exciting and challenging endeavor. The Synchron archetype is known for its ability to quickly synchro summon powerful monsters by tuning levels and utilizing various Synchron monsters. Here's a sample decklist to help you get started:

 

Main Deck (40 Cards):

  Monsters (22):

  • Junk Synchron x3
  • Quickdraw Synchron x3
  • Doppelwarrior x3
  • Synchron Explorer x2
  • Jet Synchron x3
  • Level Eater x1 (See Point 6 in Adjustments)
  • Unknown Synchron x2
  • Synchron Carrier x2
  • Rush Warrior x1
  • Effect Veiler x2

  Spells (14):

  • Tuning x3
  • Reinforcement of the Army x1
  • One for One x1
  • Foolish Burial x1
  • Upstart Goblin x1
  • Twin Twisters x2
  • Pot of Desires x2
  • Called by the Grave x3 (See Point 5)

  Traps (4):

  • Solemn Strike x2
  • Solemn Judgment x1
  • Solemn Warning x1

 

Extra Deck (15):

  Synchro Monsters (11):

  • Stardust Dragon x1
  • Shooting Quasar Dragon x1
  • Shooting Star Dragon x1
  • T.G. Hyper Librarian x1
  • Accel Synchron x1
  • Formula Synchron x1
  • T.G. Wonder Magician x1
  • Road Warrior x1
  • Jet Warrior x2
  • Black Rose Dragon x1 (See Point 1)

  Xyz Monsters (4):

  • T.G. Recipro Dragonfly x1 (See Point 2)
  • T.G. Hyper Psychic Blaster x1 (See Point 3)
  • Number 39: Utopia x1
  • Number S39: Utopia the Lightning x1

 

Side Deck (15):

  • Cosmic Cyclone x2
  • Red Reboot x2 (See Point 4)
  • Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit x3
  • Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring x3
  • Dimensional Barrier x2
  • Evenly Matched x3

 

Key Strategies:

  • Tuning and Search: Use cards like "Tuning" and "Reinforcement of the Army" to search for your Synchron monsters, particularly Junk Synchron and Quickdraw Synchron. These are essential pieces for your combos.
  • Level Manipulation: Level Eater and Synchron Carrier help manipulate levels, making it easier to summon Synchro monsters with varying levels.
  • Combo Plays: Combine Quickdraw Synchron with Doppelwarrior and Jet Synchron for explosive combo plays. Quickdraw Synchron's effect lets you summon it easily, and Jet Synchron can be sent from your hand to the graveyard to trigger its effect.
  • Synchro Climbing: Utilize the Synchron monsters and Level Eater to synchro climb into powerful Synchro monsters like Shooting Quasar Dragon and Shooting Star Dragon.
  • Draw Power: Upstart Goblin, Pot of Desires, and the Synchro monsters themselves provide card draw, helping you access key combo pieces.
  • Protection: Solemn Strike, Solemn Judgment, and Solemn Warning are used to protect your combo pieces and prevent your opponent's plays.
  • Side Deck: Customize your side deck to adapt to the current meta and the decks you frequently face. Hand traps like Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit and Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring can help disrupt your opponent's plays.

Remember that piloting a combo-heavy deck like this requires practice to master the sequencing of your plays and adapt to different situations. The extra deck also offers flexibility, so feel free to adjust it based on your preference and the decks you encounter in your local meta."

 

Adjustments:

  • 1: "Jet Black Rose Dragon" does not exist, and was replaced with Black Rose Dragon 
  • 2: "T.G. Recipro Dragonfly"  is not an Xyz monster
  • 3: "T.G. Hyper Psychic Blaster" does not exist, and was replaced with T.G. Blade Blaster 
  • 4: Red Reboot  is banned, and was replaced with Infinite Impermanence 
  • 5: Called by the Grave is Limited, and the 2 copies were replaced with 2 copies of D.D. Crow 
  • 6: Level Eater is banned, and was replaced with Junk Converter

deck_excerpt: Branded Fusion to 1? NO PROBLEM!!! COPIUM
deck_description:
I don't know what the deal with Konami is, but they seem to have a personal vendetta vs. my favourite Yugioh lore hero - Albaz!
 
 Their iconic powerful card, Branded Fusion, has been brought from the original 3, semi-limited to 2, and finally to ONE!!! Why Konami why, must Albaz (and his adoring fanbase, me included) suffer even more??? Branded is not even particularly oppressive (esp. since Expulsion has been banned) and its a general consensus that it is a fun/fair deck to fight against and pilot!
 
Perhaps Konami wants to change the strategy's identity from the over-centralizing resolution Branded Fusion to other forms of play. This harsh limit to the deck's best card forces Branded Despia players to be creative and adapt to the meta, or else they will fall behind with vs. the unstoppable progress of powercreep. 
 
Luckily with all the support Branded Despia has, they're not a one trick pony and have many other plays other than resolving Branded Fusion. There are still many ways to search and recycle Branded Fusion, so that you can be sure that you can use it multiple times over the course of a duel. 

With Tearlaments further weakened, Kashtira not at it's full power level just yet and Spright arguably the strongest deck on ladder, Branded can compete comfortably versus top tier Masterduel meta despite the seemingly critical consistency hit to Branded Fusion. Despite the 50 card decklist, getting to the one copy of Branded Fusion is still very accessible due to the many ways to tutor it out of the deck into hand, and there are multiple ways to recycle the card (that being Retribution, Tragedy and Kitt). 

The second copy of Branded Fusion has been replaced by Keeper of Dragon Magic, whose discard of a card to search any normal fusion spell can help bring a card from hand to GY, triggering Edge Imp Chain's search or enabling Despian Tragedy's GY recovery. It's ability to summon Cartesia or Albaz from the GY, albeit facedown also has some utility, since you are given another piece of material for a fusion summon. 

Other than that one minor change, the deck, strategy and win condition is functionally the same - fusion summon gigantic beatsticks and out-resource your opponent to secure the win! 

If you want a detailed guide with combos on how to pilot Branded Despia, check out my guide for August.
 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!


GLHF Duelists!

deck_excerpt: Dark Strike Fighter FTK ft. Primal Seed+Galaxy Queen's Light+Coltwing
deck_description:
Hi! In this deck, we will be dealing millions of damage with "Dark Strike Fighter", all thanks to endless cycle of "Primal Seed" and "Galaxy Queen's Light" on Coltwing. Let's jump into action!

 

(That's really a lot of damage... 999999+ damage!!!)

 

Gameplan

1) Send 2 x Coltwing to GY. You have four alternatives:

  • Special Summon one of them with Ancient to deliver as Synchro material for Librarian.
  • Discard one of them with Dugares.
  • Discard both of them with Ravenous.
  • Special Summon one of them with Saryuja and destroy it with either "Acid Rain" or "Thunder Crash".

2) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Scale and destroy all of your monsters with "Thunder Crash"...

  • Alternatively, "Dark Hole" works as well, seen in "Side Deck" but it costs SR to craft and you wouldn't want your opponent's side to be disturbed to trigger GY related effects. "Thunder Crash" is N to craft btw.

3) Special Summon "Chaos Emperor Dragon". From here on, cycle your combo pieces with "Primal Seed". As long as you target Primal Seeds each other, it won't be an issue.

4) With this setup, your Main Monster Zone should have four free spots. Fill two of them by reviving both Coltwings with "Monster Reborn". When you revive last one, you will fill last remaining spots with two tokens.

5) The current level of Coltwing is based on the sum of level of tokens and original level of Coltwing. This is addition, which is actually done only by tokens, not setting its level to fixed amount. Therefore, by playing "Galaxy Queen's Light" on Coltwing, its level will increase with respect to level of tokens. Reason is that you will also increase the level of tokens. Here is the process:

  • At first, the level of Coltwing will be level 10 >>> Coltwing (4) + Token (3) + Token (3)
  • Galaxy Queen's Light >>> Target Coltwing (level 10) >>> Tokens will be level 10
  • New calculation = Token (10) + Token (10) + Coltwing (4) = Coltwing (24)

6) Repeat the step explained in #5, by targeting only on Coltwing and nothing else.

7) When you think it's enough, play "Acid Rain" to clear up all Machines. Note that Coltwings won't be destroyed at first because tokens actually protect them. If you play for another time, Coltwings will be erased for certain.

8) It's time to bring forth "Dark Strike Fighter" but in order to do so, we need to Synchro Summon it. Just revive Stardust + Tuner with "Monster Reborn" to Synchro Summon "Dark Strike Fighter" later on.

9) Due to tokens being destroyed, level of Coltwings has been reset. Yet, remember Chaos Emperor Dragon? Play "Galaxy Queen's Light" for one last time on Chaos and then, either tribute Chaos or Coltwing with Dark Strike to deal a big damage. It's like a nuclear bomb launched right into your opponent's face, don't you think?

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Monster Reborn" is given for free, if you have completed tutorial to save 30 UR!

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contact Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Number 60: Dugares the Timeless" can be found within "Number Recall" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Pot of Acquisitiveness" + "Primal Seed" + "Ravenous" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 60 SR and 60 UR!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 60 SR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 540 SR and 120 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. Let me know if you have any questions and have fun in Master Duel!

deck_excerpt: Swing, pendulum of the soul! Draw an arc of light across the heavens! Pendulum Summon! Appear now, my monsters!
deck_description:
Due to the nature of how volitile Pendulum can be in Trinity (especially when playing around specific Effect Monsters), this is one variant of many that can be applied when taking into consideration Pendulum Magician. This build in particular aims to make the most usage of Rank 4s and Synchro 8s while also featuring a few bombs here and there that still synergize without clogging up the hand too much with non-scales. Unfortunately, losing Halqifibrax was an indirect nerf to PendMa's ability to have pressure during the opponent's turn, but it's still playable.

If you're interested in a more tempo-focused build, I'll be uploading one sometime in the future; however, I will say that Metalfoes tend to favor that style of play better as their room for mistakes and punishment is much more forgiving thanks to the abundance of searchers, Fusion Summoning, and Normal Monsters.


- Difficulty -
★★★★★
If you're going to be playing Pendulum in Trinity you should at least be forewarned that your hands will differ vastly in quality and consistency, especially the bigger your deck size is. No two openers should ever realistically be expected to be identical unless they're bridging through Extra Deck lines or engines and even then, your Pendulum composition would vary regardless of how consistent that board may've been (i.e. Bagooska/Halqi pass). You'll have to be prepared to weigh the worth of monster effects vs. necessary scales in tandem with determining if it's even worth it to commit to certain plays when faced with backrow or the dreaded Maxx "C" and Twin Twisters. Lastly, you'll also be committing Xyz materials to the GY instead of the Face-Up Extra Deck like one might be used to, so be prepared for that as well as non-archetypal cards sent there are functionally lost for the remainder of the duel without Omega.

 - Consistency -
★★★☆☆
Since our plays focus primarily on the Extra Deck and not long-winded combos like its TCG counterpart, we just need to find any two level 4s to get off to the races... or establish a Synchro play that caters to the hand's follow-up options. Finding Pendulum Call is by-far the most consistent you'll probably get to an opener though, on top of protecting your scales from counterplay. Loop it with Enlightenment Paladin to further cycle your names faster.

- Sackiness -
★★☆☆☆
Not many avenues for sacking here since your best topdecks are situational or rely on a discard to work (like Pendulum Call). The addition of Revolution Synchron allows us to Black Rose the board without having to worry about conditional play like Exciton would require of us (and is also just unlimited for some reason). Berserker allows us to steal games pretty quickly with its raw damage output. And Clear Wing just enables Raigekis when appropriate... actually... between Berserker, Paladin, Archfiend, Magma, and Rebellion, the deck just features a myriad of conversions to finish off remaining LP from alarming levels that may've seemed safe prior.

- Viability -
★★☆☆☆
Viable enough. Like any actually dedicated Pendulum deck, I would not recommend playing it blindly into a tournament without practice first. You need to be able to play through your scales getting destroyed and targeted constantly, on top of the usual suspects for disruption and interaction. You cannot expect to rely heavily on Pend Summoning in every situation and need to be able to read the situation and assess which moves give the highest payout for the amount of risk you're putting in... and most importantly... you need to be able to cope with hands that feature no low/high scales.... everysinglegoddamtime.

No longer write-up concerning strategy here. PendMa itself doesn't really have anything outside of loops with Timestar, Oaf, and Star so if that's what you're looking for you're better off relying on incorporating engines like Exosister, Performages w/ Omega loops, or just simply sacking the opponent into oblivion with Mega Kuraz + Albaz shenanigans.

45 Card Deck = 3 Points with 3p used.
1p Duelist Alliance (Extra Copy)
1p Witchcrafter Golem Aruru
.5p Pendulum Call
.5p Draco Berserker of the Tenyi

Learning Pendulum in Trinity takes some time and getting used to. Prepare to suffer some loses or call otherwise good hands clunky on first look-throughs. If you're having trouble getting used to them I strongly encourage you to check out some replays of them in action, most notably the replays concerning victories that aren't just granted to them by a single turn's OTK. You can also always review your own replays to see what you could've done differently as the nature of Pendulums in a limited format like this invite room for a myriad of different routes to be taken with hands and decisions concerning them. Most cards tend to be starters, bridges, or extenders so having to sacrifice them to the S/T for scales makes decision-making a lot less braindead than something like "NS Girsu" into your respective pivots.

Good luck.

The Level 8s, like the "Horus" monsters and Centurion Emet VI, can be used either as Synchro Material or a Rank 8 extenders, into something like Coach King Giantrainer, which draws you 3 cards. Seeing as the main objective of the deck turn 1 is to make their Level 12 Synchro Monster, Centurion Legatia, you can easily do that and set up for more synchro plays on your opponent's turn, as the "Centurion" monsters turn themselves into Traps in the backrow, allowing them to quick effect synchro with the help of their powerful Field Spell, Stand-Up Centurion!, which can also Chain Block the search effect of their archetypal Tuner, Centurion Primera, as well as start the engine by setting Centurion Trudea with its 2nd effect.

If Hot Red Dragon Archfiend King Calamity doesn't get banned by the time "Valiant Smashers" comes out, this deck will definitely get in on the forbidden list. It can easily make their archetypal synchro turn 1, then make Crimson Dragon (card) at the start of the Main Phase, enabling you to go into the King Calamity Synchro as soon as your opponent's turn starts, effectively skipping their turn. This deck is powerful, consistent, and fun, so give it a shot.

deck_excerpt: Play 20+ Cards on Turn 1 - Solitaire your way to full co-linked Tri-gate
deck_description:
This deck is based on comboing into a colink 3 Tri-Gate Wizard, and will spend almost half your cards to do it turn 1. Consistency is about 85-90%. Very weak to hand-traps though. Also weak to golem/kaijus.

---

#### Combo #1 - Magician + Shark

Magician, Shark, ss Magician, Shark to 3, ss Rat, Photon Pappi, Turn Rat, Rat ss Magician, Carrier, Carrier ss Rat, Magician ss Magician, spent Wind-Ups into Maintinence(Shark to hand), Magician ss activatable Wind-Up, Rat ss Magician, Pappi + Carrier into Phoenix, Maintinence banish Rat, Magician summon lvl3, non lvl3s into Bow Goddess with Maintinence, Rat ss Magician, Carrier, ss Bat, ss Shark from hand, Rat + Shark into Underclock, Bat grab whatever, Magician ss whatever, Underclock + any into Tri-gate, Cerberus

#### Combo #2 - Carrier(With Wind-Up Component)

Carrier ss Rat, Rat ss Wind-Up, non-Rat into Maintenance, Shark to hand, Banish Rat, Rat ss Wind-Up, Carrier, ss Magician, ss Shark, ss Magician, Shark to 3, ss Rat, Photon Pappi, Rat to attack, Rat ss Magician, Transcode with Papi and Maintinence, Carrier, ss Bat, Magician ss Magician, spent into Tri-gate, Bat grab Shark, Magician special any, ss Shark, Phoenix, Cerberus

#### Combo #3 - Carrier(With Rat Component) + Extender(Reborn/Ayers/Malfunction/ETele/Fusion/Wheeleder/Tracker/Danger/Birdman)

Carrier, ss Rat, Rat ss Rat, Maintinance(Shark to hand), banish Rat, Rat ss Rat, Carrier, ss Magician, ss Shark, ss Magician, ss Magician, Transcode Maintinence + Carrier, Extender to get lvl 3, Carrier, Underclock*, ss Bat, Tri-gate with spent cards, Bat grab Shark, Magician ss anything, ss Shark, Phoenix, Cerberus

For Birdman, bounce one of the Rats after Maintenance and go to Combo #2

#### Combo #4 - One for One + Magician + non-Bat Wind-Up
Normal magician, One for One into Bat, Bat activate, Magician ss Magician, spent into Maintinence(Shark to hand), Magician ss Magician, ss Shark, Magician ss Rat, Maintinence banish Rat, Magician ss Magician, ss Carrier, Carrier ss Rat, spent Magician and Maintinence into Transcode, spent into Cerb, Rat ss Magician, Magician ss usable Wind-Up, spent into Phoenix, activate usable Wind-Up, Magician ss usable Wind-Up2, Tri-gate

#### Combo #? - Carrier(no Wind-Ups) + Extenders

There are other combos, depending on the extenders you have in your hand, but generally they start with Carrier

###### Combo Piece - Bat + Magician

Generally the last carrier summon when you have no rats. With bat + Magician and 2 free spaces, Bat can grab Shark, Magician ss something, and Shark ss itself.

###### Combo Piece - Magician + Magician + Wind-Up Effect

Magician summons Rat. Pappiloperative can turn it back to attack position, giving an extra summon if Rat summons another Magician.

###### Combo Piece - Knightmare/Twister + Danger!?

Discarding Danger!? allows it to ss itself.

This cactus attacks but also protects! Are you interested in the setup, where your opponent will be forced to attack forever? If you are, let's go!

 

(This is an immortal Cactus!)

 

Gameplan

1) If you go first, plant at least one rose to your opponent's side with "Black Garden" but the more, the merrier. Then, destroy Garden with Ancient/Ravenous. If you go second, you can disregard this step.

2) Throughout the game, don't forget to activate "Burning Bamboo Sword" to skip your opponent's Main Phase 1. To do so, first place Burning and then, Broken. Game will ask you if you want to skip your opponent's Main Phase 1 or not, just accept it...

  • Also, try to break Broken to free up a space for "Power of the Guardians", which allows Cactus to be beefy and protected. You can do it either with Extra Deck summons or Elephant/Wonder/Knowledge plays.

3) Special Summon Cactus via Saryuja. Try Special Summoning Cactus to where Saryuja points to for minor boost and target "Power of the Guardians" on Cactus.

4) Set all traps and end your turn but not before changing "Activation Confirmation" to "Switch+Hold" and setting to "ON" in-game to not miss any action, which can be edited in "Duel" section of settings page. Then, on your opponent's turn (Draw Phase), activate Yang Zing + Final Attack...

  • In #2, we made sure our opponent's Main Phase 1 will be skipped. Next will be Battle Phase, which is where we need to lock our opponent to win with Cactus. By playing Yang Zing + Final Attack combination, not only all of monsters your opponent control will set into Attack Position but they will have to attack no matter what.
  • If they have a bigger monster than Cactus,"Power of the Guardians" will protect Cactus from the monster.

5) If your opponent tries to attack into monsters different than Cactus, redirect all and future monsters into Cactus by activating "Staunch Defender"...

  • Now, your opponent has nothing to do but to attack Cactus only.  When at least one of them are killed, Cactus will plant a token, which will be automatically turned into Attack Position with "Final Attack" and forced to attack thanks to "Yang Zing".

6) Congratulations, you win the game!

deck_excerpt: Remade my deck for a IRL sesh with an old buddy
deck_description:
Game plan: Leverage the drawn effects/engines to either board swarm and then summon big links or other boss monsters

The main opening combos differ depending on whether you go second or first:

If Going First (Req. any Level 5 in hand + Multiply + Five-star Twilight): Summon any Level 5 > use Five-star Twilight to summon the Kuribros > use the 4non-OG Kuribros to Link out Apolousa > sac OG Kuriboh w/ multiply for 5x tokens > sac two tokes to link in I:P Masquerena > sac a token to link in a Linkurboh > sac a token again for another Linkurboh > end turn > (On Opponet's Turns)  use I:P Masquerena's ability to link in Underworld Goddess with the an opponent's monster + I:P Masquerena + the two Linkurbohs > develop board from here

If Going Second (again, Req. any Level 5 in hand + Multiply + Five-star Twilight): Summon any Level 5 > use Five-star Twilight to summon the Kuribros > use 3 of non-OG Kuribros to summon Lion Heart XYZ > use the last non-OG Kuribro to link in Linkuriboh > sac OG Kuriboh w/ multiply for 4x tokens > sac a token to link in another Linkurboh > tribute the second Linkurboh + a token for any of the LINK-2 > sac a token to bring back the second Linkurboh > use the LINK-2 + the 2x Linkurboh to summon Borrelsword > tribute the last token for Secure Gardna > go for game with Borrelsword & Lion Heart

 

Some clarifications:

Astral Kuriboh can be either a level 1 or 5 to be used for five-star twilight, XYZ, or tributing.

The Dark Summoning Beast package represents a form of level 5 recursion again for Five-star Twilight or XYZ

Time to heal up your wounds and count down from 20! It has been a while since I brought up means of immortality with Final Countdown, now I have formed another. Let me explain the plan, which is not that complex but you need to act fast!

 

(Final Countdown vs Kashtira)

 

Gameplan

1) Play "Double Summon" and "Final Countdown". The effect of "Double Summon" will be used for Necroface to not deck out since we will draw a lot of cards.

2) Send 2 x Coltwing + 1 x Generator to GY. Here are the methods...

  • Dugares/Ravenous to send from hand to GY.
  • Ancient to pull off from hand and deliver to GY as Synchro material for Librarian.
  • Saryuja to pull off from hand and deliver to GY with either "Thunder Crash" or "Acid Rain".

3) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Scale and destroy all of your monsters with "Thunder Crash"...

  • Alternatively, "Dark Hole" works as well, seen in "Side Deck" but it costs SR to craft and you wouldn't want your opponent's side to be disturbed to trigger GY related effects. "Thunder Crash" is N to craft btw.

4) Special Summon "Chaos Emperor Dragon". From here on, cycle your combo pieces with "Primal Seed". As long as you target Primal Seeds each other, it won't be an issue.

5) With this setup, your Main Monster Zone should have four free spots. Fill two of them by reviving both Coltwings with "Monster Reborn". When you revive last one, you will fill last remaining spots with two tokens.

6) The current level of Coltwing is based on the sum of level of tokens and original level of Coltwing. This is addition, which is actually done only by tokens, not setting its level to fixed amount. Therefore, by playing "Galaxy Queen's Light" on Coltwing, its level will increase with respect to level of tokens. Reason is that you will also increase the level of tokens. Here is the process:

  • At first, the level of Coltwing will be level 10 >>> Coltwing (4) + Token (3) + Token (3)
  • Galaxy Queen's Light >>> Target Coltwing (level 10) >>> Tokens will be level 10
  • New calculation = Token (10) + Token (10) + Coltwing (4) = Coltwing (24)

7) Repeat the step explained in #6, by targeting only on Coltwing and nothing else.

8) When you think it's enough, play "Acid Rain" to clear up all Machines. Note that Coltwings won't be destroyed at first because tokens actually protect them. If you play for another time, Coltwings will be erased for certain.

9) Time to become immortal. Remember Chaos Emperor Dragon? Due to destruction of tokens, level of Coltwings will reset but modified level of Chaos still remains. Take advantage of it by reviving "Healing Wave Generator" with "Monster Reborn" and targeting "Chaos Emperor Dragon" to gain millions of LP...

  • You can repeat this setup as many times as you please by destroying Generator with "Acid Rain" and reviving with "Monster Reborn".

10) If you still have time, first and foremost, play Necroface. With spells banished thanks to Panda, you can reshuffle nearly a third of your Main Deck. Then, play "Pot of Avarice" a bunch of times to pile up your Main Deck with monsters as well...

  • Ideally, you should play "Pot of Avarice" step at first and when you are done, you can set all three later on to fight against Mill decks. However, if you are running out of time, play Necroface first, since it's a one card play to shuffle about 20 cards.
  • If you don't like the setup with "Pot of Avarice", or want an easy shuffler like Necroface, Exodius got you covered. Check it in "Side Deck".

11) You can end your turn now. Stalling for 20 turns shouldn't be an issue thanks to infinite amount of LP but be mindful Mill based decks. Whenever possible, shuffle cards with "Pot of Avarice" and "Pot of Acquisitiveness" to not deck out at all costs.

12) Congratulations, you win the duel with Final Countdown!

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Monster Reborn" is given for free, if you have completed tutorial to save 30 UR!

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contact Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Number 60: Dugares the Timeless" can be found within "Number Recall" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Pot of Acquisitiveness" + "Primal Seed" + "Ravenous" + "Final Countdown" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 60 SR and 90 UR!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 90 SR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 570 SR and 150 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. Let me know if you have any questions and have fun in Master Duel!

deck_name: G2ND OTK CYBER DRAGON MASTER DUEL
deck_description: DON'T FORGET TO CHECK THE REPLAY

A technically more budget* friendly version of Synchron, I wanted to try something other than Adventurer due to the current format (Post DUNE June 2023 banlist) being very Droll heavy for me. This plays much better into it, by using Neo Space Connector in tandem with Neo-Spacian Aqua Dolphin to snipe handtraps or bait them from your opponent, while not playing into Droll & Lock Bird as much. Maximizing on the more specific Tuner monsters to make it easier, while running Sakitama as another extender.

While it is weaker at going second, you can snipe even more cards from your opponents hand when going first, resulting in the ability to hand rip for 4 and still have enough negates to pretty much stop anything they can toss at you. It feels much better than the Adventurer engine, even if it comes with its own issues. But that's what the side deck is for, mostly focusing on board breakers but teching Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring for some decks that would otherwise be difficult to play into, such as Exosisters, Rescue-ACE and whatnot.

*Budget friendly as in "not as expensive as usual". I've opted to not get Revolution Synchron or Crimson Dragon since it works as it is, even if those would be to some decent help. I'm always goofing about with my decks, trying to find more viable ways or interesting techs to make it less monotone!

deck_excerpt: Boardbreakers right now in Masterduel are STRONG! Time to blind-second with Sky Striker!
deck_description:
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!


Right now, blind second strategies are in a good position to tackle the meta because of the nerf to Tearlaments - the only deck that does relatively well vs. boardbreakers. Branded isn't really at the top of the meta as well, but they also were severely nerfed due to the limit of their best card, Branded Fusion - thus weakening another deck that does well with boardbreakers. The meta decks that are in the vacuum that Tearlaments/Branded leave behind are Spright and Runick, and decks like that crack wide open under the relentless assault of boardbreaking cards and the Sky Striker engine! 

 

Basically what I'm saying is that boardbreakers right now in Masterduel are STRONG!

 

This is where Sky Strikers come in - in addition to having enough main deck space to fit in the mandatory "Maxx C" package (9 cards), the strategy can also comfortably fit powerspells like Lightning Storm, Dark Ruler No More, Raigeki and Triple Tactics Talent! The Sky Striker engine also has cards that excel at cracking boards like Widow Anchor and Afterburners. 

The time-tested strategy with blind second Sky Strikers is to destroy most if not all of your opponent's resources that they slap down on the board going first, and then close out the match with Sky Striker's grind game. This is done by setting up multi-role and if you cannot, you prioritize getting Engage! from deck and using it as much as possible especially with it's extra +1 draw.

 

This deck has cards specifically picked out for the September 2023 meta, like Triple Tactics Talent (super good since everyone uses Spright, Tear, and handtraps, etc).

The current meta allows for Lightning Storm and Raigeki to obliterate most duelist's boards this format since they generally spend all their resources building their "unbreakable" board only to fall to 1-2 cards. For example, you can bait out your opponent's singular S/T negate (Like Spright Carrot/Baronne) with Afterburners then obliterate everything afterwards with Raigeki! If that's not enough, Raye and friends can clear the board very well during the battle phase and with Zeke's banish. 


If your weakened opponent hasn't surrendered yet due to the sheer resource advantage and offensive pressure this deck generates, you can clear the board with a plethora of cards including Linkage, allowing Raye to OTK all by herself!

If you have any questions about this deck, feel free to ask me in the comments below!

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

deck_name: Chimera Runick (September 2023 Post Sao Paulo YCS)
deck_description:
Hello there !

 

Since its release in DUNE, I'm hyped by the Chimera variants. This archetype provides consistancy, generates some card advantage and provides some negates and hand disruption. And as a tiny engine, it can be mixed with other complementary archetypes like Branded. Then, I decided to test Runick Chimera as this variant is surprising overall and because of the ressource generation the deck is capable of (draw 3 with Fountain + draw 2 with Guardian Chimera) 

This is a sample list for the Runick Chimera strategy. I was mainly inspired by Joshua Schmidt testing and by the topping list for the conception of mine. I'm not an expert of Runick : feel free to give your advices and feedbacks in comments

Enjoy !

deck_excerpt: Destiny Board ft. Arcana+Sentence of Doom+Trap Reclamation
deck_description:
Hi there! It has been a while since I played Destiny Board deck. I decided to revisit my old deck and put a new twist. Take as many turns as you like and win the game with Destiny Board. Let me show you.

 

Gameplan

1) Reach the board state as illustrated:

  • After placing "Light Barrier", Arcana was Special Summoned by Saryuja. After choosing the outcome as heads, you can send two of your monsters to GY and take an extra turn. Make sure your side of battlefield is full of monsters but it's alright to miss one or two.
  • "Into the Void" was played. Therefore, Sabres + Balerdroch will be delivered to GY, which is what we want. Reason is that you can Special Summon both from GY to your side and use both to take as many turns as you need.
  • All traps were set and all of letters will be delivered to GY, which is fine. "Sentence of Doom" can find three letters and "Trap Reclamation" can allow you to repeat "Sentence of Doom" one more time to find last letter.
  • Don't change button to anything other than "Auto". Never set to "OFF". "ON" can ask meaningless confirmations, so "Auto" should be fine from now on.

 

2) It's your turn now, if you have used the ability of Arcana. When you are in Standby Phase, activate your first trap, which is "Destiny Board". Then, chain into "Sentence of Doom" (SoD) but don't use its effect yet when asked to. Start putting letters when you are in Main Phase 1, which is when you should activate SoD. Next, you should chain into "Trap Reclamation" to retrieve SoD after you have put a letter. Although I forgot doing it, I did "Sentence of Doom >>> Trap Reclamation" chain on next turn, not a big deal:

  • In case you wonder, Sabres was Special Summoned by shuffling a card you have on top of your deck. Balerdroch has arrived during your Standby Phase, thanks to a field spell present on the battlefield.
  • While using the ability of SoD, there is an option related to Fiend monsters. Since Sabres is a Fiend monster, this option will always appear to you until he arrives on the battlefield. Just don't pick up this option by accident or you will miss your chance of putting a letter. Reason is that you can only use one effect per turn and only once that turn. What a harsh condition, this is the example of "hard once per turn" effect.
  • As always, don't forget to send Sabres + Balerdroch to GY for extra turn with Arcana.

 

3) Let's make up for the mistake I did in #2. I forgot "Sentence of Doom >>> Trap Reclamation" chain, but this time, I did. Have a look at pictures for better understanding:

 

4) For your next two turns, place Sabres + Balerdroch from GY to battlefield. On your Main Phase 1, place your letters with SoD. Then, send Sabres + Balerdroch to GY for extra turn thanks to Arcana, both of which will come back to life anyways. With all five letters present on your board, you win the duel:

  • If you want to watch it in action, click here!

 

Your fate has brought you here to save up SR and UR points. Let's have a look:

- "Allure of Darkness" + "Into The Void" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Arcana Force" + "Light Barrier" can be found within "Hand of Fate" Secret Pack to save 30 SR and 30 UR!

- "Doomking Balerdroch" can be found within "Abyssal Underworld" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 90 SR!

- "Destiny Board" can be found within "The Trap in the Wicked Castle" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

deck_excerpt: Master Duel and/or OCG (and TCG) deck that I've been testing with A LOT. The deck is the ultimate board breaker
deck_description:
Thunder Dragons are a fast tempo deck that excel at completely destroying and breaking an enemy board. You put so much pressure on your opponent and have so much interaction. I truly think this deck has a spot in the current meta as a threatening rogue deck. Against slower control decks you can easily smash down the fort. I have been subject testing this deck all Summer and I think I'm finally confident enough to share what I believe is the safest and most optimal build of Thunder Dragons

THUNDER DRAGON ARCHETYPE: 

For those who aren't aware of how this deck operates. Thunder Dragons are a deck that revolve around discarding copies of Thunder Dragon and Thunder Dragondark from your hand, which will trigger the powerful effect of Thunder Dragon Titan . What makes the big bad Titan so terrifying is that it's not a once per turn, so you can keep discarding cards to Titan and just completely nuke your opponent's board! OR; you discard Thunder Dragondark and Thunder Dragonmatrix as a Quick Effect and start disrupting your opponent's board!

Thunder Dragon Titan also has protection, making him an amazing tank and not just a glass cannon. By banishing any 2 cards from your graveyard. Titan can protect himself from destruction effects, and once again it's not a once per turn! So as long as you have fuel in the graveyard. Titan can just keep protecting himself over and over.

Titan's sidekick and partner in crime is the equally frightening Thunder Dragon Colossus! Which is one of your best going first monsters. Preventing your opponent from searching their deck is a ruthless floodgate.

 

How to Summon Thunder Dragon Titan easily

Thunder Dragon Titan is summoned in 1 of 2 ways. The first is by loading up your Graveyard and Banish zone with 3 Thunder monsters and then using Thunder Dragon Fusion . The graveyard can easily be loaded up by discard Thunder Dragon . Thunder Dragon says "up to 2 copies" meaning you can discard 1 Thunder Dragon, and just get 1. Then repeat the process. So now you have 2 Thunder Dragons in the Graveyard and only 1 in hand. Now you just a Thunder to normal summon. Like Batteryman Solar (which puts more Thunders in the GY btw.) or Thunder Dragonmatrix .
Now that you've shuffled the 2 Thunder Dragons back into your deck. You can now use that 3rd Thunder Dragon in your hand and keep discarding it. Which will trigger Thunder Dragon Titan! 

The second method is my personal favorite. It uses Ready Fusion to summon Kaminari Attack.
Thunder Dragon Titan has an alternative summoning method. If you have 1 Thunder in your hand, you can banish that Thunder and Kaminari Attack to easily summon him! 

All the new main deck Thunder Dragon monsters also all have a secondary banished effect. If they get banished, they provide you with so much utility! 
Thunder Dragonhawk is a free magical mallet. If he's banished, we can shuffle all our bricks back into our deck, then draw cards. And if we draw a copy of Thunder Dragondark, Thunder Dragonmatrix or Thunder Dragon, that gives Thunder Dragon Titan more fuel to further blow up the board! 

Thunder Dragondark's banish effect is my personal favorite. As it's a free search for ANY other Thunder Dragon card. Usually you're gonna want to grab Thunder Dragon or Thunder Dragonmatrix. 

Thunder Dragonroar is also very good. Allowing us to Special Summon a Thunder Dragon monster from the deck. And you can either bounce it to your hand. (If you do, special summon Thunder Dragondark so you can activate Titan during your opponent's turn) or use it as fodder. Because by having a non-Fusion Thunder monster. We can tribute it to easily special summon Thunder Dragon Colossus through his alternative summoning condition.

THE CHAOS SUPPORT

If you've noticed. All the good Thunder Dragon monsters love being banished, AND they're all either Light or Dark. Allowing us to fill up the remaining slots in our deck with powerful Chaos Monsters. Chaos Space allows us to not only put Thunders into the GY, but also allows us to search for our Chaos Monsters. I currently play 4 chaos monsters. 

Black Luster Soldier - Envoy of the Beginning : It's the best Light Chaos Monster you can search for. And while you usually want to search for a Dark Chaos Monster. Sometimes, you only have Darks in your hand. BLS also has a very relevant ability in the form of Banishing enemy monsters. Thunder Dragon Titan usually just destroys stuff. But what if a monster can't be destroyed by card effects? BLS has got you covered! It also has the potential for an OTK with it's second ability allowing it to attack twice. 

Chaos Emperor, the Dragon of Armageddon : One of the best instant nukes in the deck. Armageddon Dragon also has some very sneaky wording. It doesn't destroy, target or banish anything. Its effect just SENDS things to the Graveyard! So it's another tool to kill proplematic indestructible monsters. 

Chaos Dragon Levianeer : Probably the best Chaos monster. It's a swiss army knife of utility. If you only banish Lights, we can revive a Thunder in the graveyard, which we can then tribute to summon Thunder Dragon Colossus! Or if you banish only darks. You get the ruthless effect of disrupting your opponent's hand, if you get lucky and snipe the right card, you'll probably just win the game off of that. But the most common effect you'll be using is the mixed effect when you banish Lights and Darks. Which allows you to destroy any 2 cards. And this destruction effect doesn't target btw!

Thunder Dragonduo : A Chaos Monster that's also a Thunder. Which means you can tribute it for Colossus, or you can banish it from your hand to summon Titan. Past that, it has no real added utility. I like it because it is an easy, searchable Thunder monster. But you can easily replace Duo with any other Chaos Monster. 

COMBOS

I already explained the go-to combos. But there are some less obvious combos that should be explained. 

Gold Sarcophagus is really funny in this deck. Because we actively want to banish our own cards. So Gold Sarcophagus is just a more powerful Foolish Burial for this deck. Gold Sarc is also an effect that can't be disrupted by Ash Blossom or other common hand traps. The cards you always want to banish will be Thunder Dragondark or Thunder Dragonroar. 

Normal Summons. 

Thunder Dragons don't usually normal summon, but they have a few normal summons that can help you combo off. 

Batteryman Solar , as previously mentioned, allows you to dump Thunders into the graveyard. Which we then will want to revive with Monster Reborn or Thunder Dragonhawk which can start a combo that eventually allows us to summon Titan and/or Colossus

Thunder Dragonmatrix is a funny normal summon. Because you can tribute it to summon Colossus. 

BOARD BREAKERS & DISRUPTION

Your main goal with this deck is to break the board. But in 2023, it can be a little difficult. Monsters nowadays have so many abilities, and many of them can't be targeted or destroyed by card effects, which are problematic because your main form of removal is by targeting and destroying things with Thunder Dragon Titan. So the remaining spell/traps are here to specifically allow us to achieve our endgame goal of board breaking and destroying everything.

Dark Ruler No More is a card I've fallen in love with! This card is awesome! Allowing us to negate all our opponent's monsters is perfect for us! With no abilities. Thunder Dragon Titan is free to blow up anything and everything you want! 

Effect Veiler and Infinite Impermanence fill a similar role as Dark Ruler No More, but only negate 1 monster, and there's no downside to them like Dark Ruler's downside of making all damage we do 0. And sometimes, you only need to negate the effects or 1 problematic monster. These 2 cards are also very good disruption during your opponent's turn. 

Book of Moon is pretty similar to the previous 3 cards mentioned, its another way to "negate" monsters. It also helps us deal with gigantic monsters that Thunder Dragon Titan can't beat over in battle. Which can be annoying. I also just really really like Book of Moon for it's utility and disruption. It's also only an R on Master Duel, making it the best budget removal.

Forbidden Droplet is the last effect negate we use. It fills double duty of loading up the graveyard with Thunders and negating effects. 

Raigeki can probably be replaced with literally anything else. You don't need Raigeki, but it has some useful moments. Raigeki is good when your opponent has a whole bunch of backrow. You negate all the monster effects, then blow up all monsters with Raigeki, and THEN we use Titan's effects to start blowing up enemy spell traps. (You can also use Harpie's Feather Duster and go vice versa. Nuking all backrow and then blowing up monsters with Titan. Use whichever you prefer)

The remaining cards are just some powerful disruption to stop your opponent from going full combo. 

THE EXTRA DECK

Another thing I love about Thunder Dragons is that the only cards that're mandatory for the extra deck are Thunder Dragon Titan , Thunder Dragon Colossus , Kaminari Attack and Chaos Angel . So you are kinda free to play around with your extra deck and do whatever you like.

I personally loaded up my extra deck with more gaint threats (I just love giant monsters) that further fuel are gameplan of disrupting the opponent and/or board breaking. 

Sea Monster of Theseus is here because it's a Ready Fusion target. And most of the Thunder Dragons you'll be summoning are level 5. Allowing us to go into Baronne de Fleur if we need to. 

IMPORTANT

If you're gonna play this deck IRL. You should be playing Instant Fusion as well. Because unfortunately, it's banned on Master Duel. 
Instant Fusion acts as a 4th copy of Ready Fusion and also has some neat utility. Allowing you to go into Thousand-Eyes Restrict and Millennium-Eyes Restrict. Which act as even more removal. If Instant Fusion is ever unbanned from Master Duel, I implore you, you should 1,000% be putting it in your deck and put Thousand Eyes & Millennium in your Extra Deck. 

The "Sideboard" 

Much like all my Master Duel Decks. The Sideboard is just a collection of cards that I recommend you use for specific matchups. Or to use them to fix some weaknesses with the deck.

Compulsory Evacuation Device and Get Out! are fantastic pieces of removal that I've used many times in the past for this deck. They're great because they get around indestructible monsters that can't be destroyed. 

Thunder Dragonlord is another big beatstick you can use. It has the awesome ability to protect your Thunder Dragon Titan. Which is amazing! But the problem is, it's a Level 9, so it can't be searched by Chaos Space...

Sales Ban and Crossout Designator are used primarily to negate Maxx C and other frustrating hand-traps. 

Speaking of Maxx "C", the only reason I've used this card is to allow us to draw more Thunders that we can use as fuel for Titan. 

Chaos Emperor Dragon - Envoy of the End is another giant nuke. Great for closing out games and good for banishing Thunders. I only recommend it because CED is an R on Master Duel, so it is much easier to obtain compared to Levianeer or Armageddon

GAMEPLAN

Going First or Second usually doesn't matter for Thunder Dragons. Both options are equally good for this deck. 

Going First allows you to summon Colossus and Titan and then belligerently disrupt your opponent, denying them the chance to break your board.

Going Second allows you to break through just about any board. 

Personally, I prefer going first, as I think it's better to have Colossus and Titan in play and put constant pressure on the opponent, never giving them any breathing room and denying every attempt they make to stop you.

Overall:

Thunder Dragons are an AMAZING deck that shouldn't be underestimated. Titan is not only a gigantic 3200atk monster, but it also has a spammable destruction effect. Colossus also puts in so much work, locking your opponent out of searching their deck can win games all on its own.

I highly encourage you to give this deck a try! As more and more cards get banned and unbanned. This deck will just keep on getting better and better.
Circular unlimited pls :)

deck_excerpt: Spright Adventurer / 19th at Las Vegas WCQ Regional Qualifier
deck_description:
I piloted this deck to 19th at the Las Vegas WCQ Regional on September 2nd, 2023. The deck's main strategy is to use Iblee to lock your opponent while still having an endboard with plenty of negates and interaction if your opponents has the out to the lock. This variant of the deck loses to Droll, so I found myself frequently using Prosperity to dig for the Called by the Grave. If the opponent doesn't Droll me there, then it's great to use as insurance for resolving Gigantic. Foolish Burial is also an amazing card in this build; it gave me access to Water Enchantress or Angler, depending on what I needed. Fateful is great for getting Angler out of your hand as well, as you can use it to send to grave upon resolution of searching the Gryphon Rider. I used Dogoran as my Kaiju of choice, because I was able to use Ninja Shadow Mosquito to put a counter on it and burn my opponent for game due to the high attack on it. However, it was still low enough for me to beat over it with Gigantic, if the Mosquito win-con was so longer an option.

I dropped my first two rounds to Unchained/Vanquish Soul and Purrely after losing both die-rolls and shaking some nerves off, as this was my first regional event ever. I won the next 7 rounds straight against Branded/Chimera, Purrely (2x), Plunder Patroll, Kashtira, Rikka/Sunavalon and Infernoble to make the Top 32 cut and receive a national invite.

The Spirit and the Cyberdark cards provide additional level 4 material in addition to your regular Normal Summon.

This deck is very powerful and can steal wins against top meta decks using monsters typically not seen in Earth machines (namely, Naturia Beast and Baronne de Fleur). These synchro monsters are made possible through Magical Hound, which can be searched easily through Gear Gigant X or milled and summoned with a Vernusylph. The deck is very consistent with many searches and draws. You do not need multiple copies of Baronne or Beast, but can be beneficial because Extrav is played. There are also tons of flex spots that can help the deck adjust with the meta. 41 card deck to lower the odds of drawing the brick (Unclaspare).

Basic Machina combo line:

  • Normal Gearframe > search Unclaspare (the mill effect locks you into machines) > mill one of the big Machinas, depending on need > overlay Gear Gigant X > search Magical Hound > overlay Drill Driver.

"Spice" combos:

  • Magical Hound + Any of the level four Earth monsters = Naturia Beast
    • Beast can be revived easily with any Vernusylph or Drill Driver
    • If you have Regulus in hand (which can be searched with Metalcruncher), target and equip Gearframe. Gearframe can then summon itself and be used as the level four Earth monster.
  • Magical Hound + Metalcruncher = Baronne de Fleur
    • This can be easily summoned going second with Urgent Schedule
  • All of the main combo monsters in the deck can be found some how with a Vernusylph: The Vernusylph to mill + any other Vernusylph.
  • Lord of the Heavenly Prison is a level 10 that can be overlayed to summon the Superdreadnoughts.

deck_description:
Noble Knights are a TCG exclusive which focuses on equipping Noble Arms to your monsters to gain their effects.

Noble Knights of the Round Table - (Level 4 Light Warriors)

  • Noble Knight Artorigus is a Light Normal monster that uh... Camelot, Camelot, Realm of Noble Knights and Noble Arms is a Field Spell that can replace itself with Noble Knights of the Round Table and either add a Noble Arms or summon an Artorigus monster from your Deck or GY, this makes Arthur a playable card in the Deck besides giving you ways to reborn the XYZ's and facilitates some combo lines if you were to be disrupted by giving you an additional body. Round Table is not bad either with some highrolls letting you summon Monsters from your GY after you Foolish Burial them with Table, which facilitate some cards like Noble Knight Drystan or Noble Knight Bedwyr. Camelot also comes back next turn after replacing itself, letting you pop a Noble Arms to protect your cards from being destroyed, considering most of them re-equip you aren't losing much + you get to use Drystan's effect.
  • Noble Knight Brothers gets you two bodies from the hand and they can recycle 3 Noble Knights or Noble Arms to draw 1. Biggest problem about this card? Turns Mordred off and its an Imperm/Veiler magnet + doesn't summon from the GY cause we couldnt have nice things back when this was released. But its pretty good for follow-up in the subsequent turns.
  • Noble Knight Gawayn is a free Special if you control a Normal Light monster, most of the Noble Knights that need an Equip are treated as a Normal monster on the field. Same goes to Noble Knight Custennin but this one requires an Noble Arms to do so, and if used as Link/XYZ/Synchro material you get an extra Normal summon for a Noble Knight monster.
  • Noble Knight Iyvanne on equip summons a Token and thats it really, you normally want to run 1 but since its part of a crucial line which gives us easy access to Isolde you could run it at 2 too.
  • Noble Knight Drystan gets to protect your Nobles from card effects if they have less than 1800 ATK and if he gets equipped he gets to pop a card, you will usually be summoning him via Isolde, Until Noble Arms or Table to get him onto the field while Camelot helps with the re-equipping shenanigans.

Betrayers of the Round Table - (Level 5 Dark Warriors)

All "Betrayers" as I will call them become Level 5 Dark Warriors upon being equipped.

  • Noble Knight Medraut is the most important card in the Deck, being your starter and such, you can destroy any Equip Spell that is equipped to him to summon from your Deck any other Noble Knight, Ivan most of the time, you have to control no other monsters to do this. You may think the condition of destroying an Equip is harsh but most of them just re-equip to another monster, in this case Ivan to get your Token to Link and XYZ.
  • Noble Knight Borz when equipped can reveal 3 "Noble Arms" and add 1 to your hand randomly and send the other ones to the GY, My Friend Purrely wishes it was this good. You will be mostly adding Camelot, setting up your Equips for your XYZ or sending your Trap which can E-teli a Noble Knight next turn.
  • Noble Knight Eachtar is just another way to go into R5nks, recurs every turn by banishing 2 Noble Knights. Same goes for his half brother Ignoble Knight of Black Laundsallyn which special summons himself by sending a Light Normal to the GY, his other effect allows him to tribute a Noble to fetch a Noble Arms. Laundsallyn is better in the grind since Camelot will be bringing Artorigus every turn back, while Eachtar is better in the earlier stages that you have more mills from Round Table.

Noble Arms (Backrow)

  • You might have seen this card before, Heritage of the Chalice is a Reinforcement of the Army for Noble Knights and Noble Arms with a recursion effect if your opponent destroys an equipped Noble Knight.
  • Until Noble Arms are Needed Once Again excavates cards up to the number of Arms you have on the field, adding 1 one of them to your hand. Its most important effect is the one to E-teli any of your Nobles in the next turn after its sent to the GY, making it the best target to send via Borz.

Lightning round for the Equips:

  • Noble Arms of Destiny protects a monster from being destroyed by battle or card effect once, re-equips when sent to the GY.
  • Noble Arms - Gallatin gives the equipped monster 1000ATK but it loses 200ATK in the standby, re-equips when sent to the GY.
  • Noble Arms - Caliburn gives the equipped monster 500ATK, soft once per turn gives you 500LP, re-equips when sent to the GY.
  • Noble Arms - Clarent you can pay 500LP to let the equipped monster attack directly, re-equips when sent to the GY.
  • Noble Arms - Arfeudutyr makes the monster lose 500 ATK to pop a set card, re-equips when sent to the GY.
  • Noble Arms - Excaliburn stops the monster from being targeted, the next turn after its sent to the GY you can replace one of your XYZ's with another one with a different name, the materials do transfer.

Royalty (Extra Deck)

  • Let's start with the most infamous card of all Noble Knights, Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights, they need no introduction, the queens of FTKs and jank Warrior-piles. On summon adds any Warrior from your Deck but you cant summon or use their effect and you can send as many Equips from the Deck to the GY to summon a Warrior whose level is equal to the number of sent Equips. She is the most important card in the combo and the biggest Ash magnet in the Deck.
  • Artorigus, King of the Noble Knights on summon Equips himself with 3 Arms from your GY, you can detach 1 material to pop as many Spells/Traps equal to the number of Arms you control. This is used mostly to reset or change who is equipped with what. Normally capping at 3500ATK and being protected by Excaliburn.
  • Sacred Noble Knight of King Custennin can detach as many materials as he want to bounce an equal ammount of cards the opponent controls. And if destroyed by battle or card effect he summons from your Extra Deck a Noble Knight XYZ with a different name attaching itself to it as a material. 
  • Sacred Noble Knight of King Artorigus like his R4nk self equips 3 on summon, you can detach 1 to pop a card and when destroyed reborns a level 4 or lower Noble. Very underwhelming for the final boss but we take what we can.

Combo:

Medraut + any Re-equip

Mordred normal > Effect destroys Re-equip > summon Ivan > Re-equip to Ivan and summon a token > Isolde add any (Eachtar or Brothers) > Send Excaliburn, Gallatin, Destiny and Arfeudutyr > summon any and make Custonnin or Artorigus. If you have another equip in hand you can summon Borz via Mordred to get Camelot and Until in the GY and then make Isolde with that, Camelot putting the other 4 in the field or just using any of your extenders from the hand.

deck_excerpt: Infernoble Knight / Louisville WCQ Regional Top 8
deck_description:
Category: Tournament Meta Deck

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Rudy Torres

Tournament: Louisville WCQ Regional - September 2nd 2023 

Placement: Top 8
Every train-based monster currently in the TCG Speed Duel pool. God I hope they add more.

A bunch of normal level 3s that can be summoned with Enchanting Fitting Room and can be protected by Justi-Break. Maybe include a boss like Blue-Eyes White Dragon or Metal Armored Bug or just roll with the level 3s.

This deck version just trying to just consistantly set up a Stars Align turn one. As much as I like going second, there's a variety of decks that use the same tools but set up better locks or end the game more consistently. Also Yata is a bad card. So with a deck that can run as many consistency tools as spirits, I thought to just run as much as possible. Nikitama is an upstart in most hands, Crane is the only good wind Spirit, and their all level 4 which enables a dugaress play. Dogmatika is half a ritual plus an upstart. This normally somewhere between 2-4 draws per turn, which helps a lot.

Normally, the field spell plus a nothing spirit is 2/3rds of the set up. You just need to be able to grab a singular piece of the combo. Aratama plus the field spell is full combo. Use the field spell to summon the L4 Baron, use its effect to either grab Aratama or the L4 Baroness and Calling(Then use the Aratama to seach said Baroness.) Use Calling to summon the Baroness, then search power spot. In the end phase, the baroness returns to hand triggering both Power Spot and Himigori. Himigori set Stars Align, and power spot search whichever piece of the combo, either the ritual spell or big monster. Unfortunatly, if you don't have both, this set-up is dead. Also, you need to have one of the big monsters in deck as well in order to get Stars align in grave, which is why we run 3 of the big rituals.

This means you can either bounce 3 monsters or Shuffle 3 backrow and sometimes set up an Amano lock. My big issue with running more Amano is that unfortuntlely it is a kind of brick in hand. I keep messing around with its ratio's and its probably best at 2, but I wanted to run some other funny cards so...

The Dogmatika package is fairly self-explantory with it being generic consitency and sending Herald of Arc Light, with the @ignister being there as a 3rd target to send of Nadir/Maximus turn 1, other extra deck bulk is avaliable. So are Ash and Book of Moon. The execption to this decks goal, because I think the card is funny (and the only non-shino WIND Ritual which does anything) is [Raging Storm Dragon - Beaufort IX,] part of what appears to be the 'what can we put on a battle handtrap and make it still god awful' competition which Konami sometimes makes an addition to. Its only summonable by Himigori (The named ritual spell on it is god-awful, requiring exact levels) This ones random benefit to the deck is that it is a) a ritual you can summon first turn sometimes which is an interuption and is a wind monster which triggers both Power Spot and Himigori. Then it also can blank a big monster's attack which is nice.

Overall the deck is exactly one good WIND spirit monster away from being super consitent, but for now, its just a fairly consistent rogue deck that sets up a floodgate. But also runs spirits, which makes it infinitely funnier.
